import { Aside } from '@astrojs/starlight/components';

`#[neo_entry]` marks a function as a contract lifecycle entry point. The most common use is the `_deploy` entry point, which the Neo runtime calls once when the contract is first deployed to the blockchain.

## Basic Usage

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;

#[neo_entry]
pub fn deploy() {
    // one-time initialization logic
}
```

The macro preserves the original function and emits a Wasm custom section containing entry point metadata:

```json
{
  "entry": {
    "name": "deploy",
    "kind": "deploy"
  }
}
```

The translator reads this metadata to wire the function as the contract's `_deploy` handler in the generated NeoVM bytecode.

## Deployment Initialization

The deploy entry point runs exactly once -- when the contract is first published to the blockchain. Use it for initialization logic that must happen before any contract method is called:

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;

#[neo_contract]
pub struct MyToken;

#[neo_entry]
pub fn deploy() {
    // Set the contract owner to the deployer
    // Initialize the total supply
    // Mint initial tokens to the owner
}
```

### Common Initialization Tasks

| Task | Description |
|---|---|
| Set owner | Store the deployer's script hash as the contract owner |
| Initialize supply | Write the initial token supply to storage |
| Mint tokens | Allocate initial tokens to the owner or a distribution address |
| Set defaults | Write default configuration values to storage |
| Emit event | Fire a deployment event for indexers and block explorers |

## Practical Example

A token contract with a deploy entry point that initializes storage:

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;
use neo_devpack::serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

neo_manifest_overlay!(
    r#"{
    "name": "DeployExample",
    "supportedstandards": ["NEP-17"]
}"#
);

#[derive(Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[neo_storage]
pub struct TokenStorage {
    balances: NeoMap<NeoByteString, NeoInteger>,
    metadata: NeoMap<NeoString, NeoValue>,
}

#[neo_contract]
pub struct DeployableToken;

#[neo_entry]
pub fn deploy() {
    let context = match NeoRuntime::get_storage_context() {
        Ok(ctx) => ctx,
        Err(_) => return,
    };

    let owner = match NeoRuntime::get_calling_script_hash() {
        Ok(hash) => hash,
        Err(_) => return,
    };

    let mut storage = TokenStorage::load(&context);

    // Mint entire supply to the deployer
    let total_supply = NeoInteger::new(1_000_000);
    storage.balances.insert(owner, total_supply);

    // Store contract metadata
    storage.metadata.insert(
        NeoString::from_str("name"),
        NeoValue::from(NeoString::from_str("DeployableToken")),
    );

    let _ = storage.save(&context);
}

#[neo_contract]
impl DeployableToken {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self
    }

    #[neo_method(safe)]
    pub fn total_supply() -> i64 {
        1_000_000
    }

    #[neo_method(safe)]
    pub fn balance_of(account: i64) -> i64 {
        // read from storage
        0
    }

    #[neo_method]
    pub fn transfer(from: i64, to: i64, amount: i64) -> bool {
        from > 0 && to > 0 && amount > 0
    }
}
```

<Aside type="caution">
  The deploy function runs in the context of the deployment transaction. If it aborts (panics or hits a VM fault), the entire deployment fails and the contract is not published. Keep initialization logic simple and handle errors gracefully.
</Aside>

## Entry Point Naming

The function name determines the `kind` field in the metadata. The translator recognizes these conventions:

| Function name | Entry kind | Neo lifecycle event |
|---|---|---|
| `deploy` | `deploy` | `_deploy` -- called on first deployment |
| `update` | `update` | Called on contract update |
| `destroy` | `destroy` | Called on contract destruction |

```rust
#[neo_entry]
pub fn deploy() {
    // first deployment
}

#[neo_entry]
pub fn update() {
    // contract update / migration
}

#[neo_entry]
pub fn destroy() {
    // cleanup before destruction
}
```

## Relationship with `#[neo_contract]`

`#[neo_entry]` is independent of `#[neo_contract]`. The entry function is a free function, not a method on the contract struct. This separation keeps lifecycle logic distinct from business logic:

```rust
// Lifecycle -- free function
#[neo_entry]
pub fn deploy() {
    let mut contract = MyToken::new();
    let _ = contract.initialize();
}

// Business logic -- struct methods
#[neo_contract]
pub struct MyToken;

#[neo_contract]
impl MyToken {
    pub fn new() -> Self { Self }

    #[neo_method]
    pub fn initialize(&mut self) -> NeoResult<()> {
        // initialization logic
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

<Aside type="note">
  The deploy entry point can instantiate the contract struct and call its methods. This is a common pattern for bridging lifecycle events into the contract's method-based API.
</Aside>

## See Also

- [#[neo_contract]](/sdk/macros/neo-contract/) -- the contract struct and impl block macros
- [#[neo_storage]](/sdk/macros/neo-storage/) -- persistent storage for initialization data
- [Contract Anatomy](/concepts/contract-anatomy/) -- full contract structure overview

import { Aside } from '@astrojs/starlight/components';

`#[neo_event]` transforms a Rust struct into a contract event. The macro generates an `emit()` method that sends a runtime notification and embeds ABI metadata into a Wasm custom section so the translator can populate the manifest's `abi.events` array.

## Basic Usage

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;

#[neo_event]
pub struct Transfer {
    pub from: NeoByteString,
    pub to: NeoByteString,
    pub amount: NeoInteger,
}
```

This generates:

1. An `impl Transfer` block with an `emit(&self) -> NeoResult<()>` method.
2. A Wasm custom section containing the event's ABI metadata (name, parameter names, parameter types).

## Emitting Events

Construct the event struct and call `emit()`:

```rust
let event = Transfer {
    from: sender_hash,
    to: receiver_hash,
    amount: NeoInteger::new(1000),
};
event.emit()?;
```

Under the hood, `emit()` does the following:

1. Creates a `NeoArray` and pushes each field as a `NeoValue`.
2. Calls `NeoRuntime::notify()` with the struct name as the event label and the array as the notification state.

The event name in the manifest matches the struct name exactly. `Transfer` produces `"name": "Transfer"` in the ABI.

## Field Requirements

The macro requires a struct with **named fields**. Unit structs and tuple structs are rejected at compile time:

```rust
// Works
#[neo_event]
pub struct Transfer {
    pub from: NeoByteString,
    pub to: NeoByteString,
    pub amount: NeoInteger,
}

// Compile error: #[neo_event] requires a struct with named fields
#[neo_event]
pub struct BadEvent(i64, i64);

// Compile error: #[neo_event] requires a struct with named fields
#[neo_event]
pub struct EmptyEvent;
```

Each field becomes a parameter in the manifest's event entry. The field name maps to the parameter name, and the field type maps to the parameter type using the SDK's type mapping rules.

## Type Mapping

Field types are mapped to Neo manifest types during code generation:

| Rust type | Manifest type |
|---|---|
| `NeoInteger` / `i64` / `i32` | `Integer` |
| `NeoBoolean` / `bool` | `Boolean` |
| `NeoString` | `String` |
| `NeoByteString` | `ByteArray` |
| `NeoArray` | `Array` |
| `NeoMap` | `Map` |
| Other | `Any` |

## Generated Manifest Metadata

For the `Transfer` event above, the macro embeds this ABI fragment:

```json
{
  "abi": {
    "events": [
      {
        "name": "Transfer",
        "parameters": [
          { "name": "from", "type": "ByteArray" },
          { "name": "to", "type": "ByteArray" },
          { "name": "amount", "type": "Integer" }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

The translator merges this into the final manifest alongside method metadata and overlay data.

## Multiple Events

A contract can define as many events as needed. Each `#[neo_event]` struct generates its own ABI entry:

```rust
#[neo_event]
pub struct Transfer {
    pub from: NeoByteString,
    pub to: NeoByteString,
    pub amount: NeoInteger,
}

#[neo_event]
pub struct Approval {
    pub owner: NeoByteString,
    pub spender: NeoByteString,
    pub amount: NeoInteger,
}

#[neo_event]
pub struct ContractUpdate {
    pub old_version: NeoString,
    pub new_version: NeoString,
    pub updated_by: NeoByteString,
}
```

## Complete Example

A token contract that emits a `Transfer` event on every successful transfer:

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;

neo_manifest_overlay!(
    r#"{
    "name": "EventExample",
    "supportedstandards": ["NEP-17"]
}"#
);

#[neo_event]
pub struct Transfer {
    pub from: NeoByteString,
    pub to: NeoByteString,
    pub amount: NeoInteger,
}

#[neo_contract]
pub struct TokenContract;

#[neo_contract]
impl TokenContract {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self
    }

    #[neo_method]
    pub fn transfer(from: i64, to: i64, amount: i64) -> bool {
        if from <= 0 || to <= 0 || amount <= 0 || from == to {
            return false;
        }

        // In production: update storage balances here

        // Emit the transfer event
        let event = Transfer {
            from: NeoByteString::from_slice(&from.to_le_bytes()),
            to: NeoByteString::from_slice(&to.to_le_bytes()),
            amount: NeoInteger::new(amount),
        };
        let _ = event.emit();

        true
    }
}
```

<Aside type="note">
  The NEP-17 standard requires a `Transfer` event on every successful transfer, including mints (where `from` is null) and burns (where `to` is null). Omitting the event makes the contract non-compliant.
</Aside>

## Error Handling

`emit()` returns `NeoResult<()>`. The call can fail if the runtime notification syscall fails. In practice this is rare, but production contracts should handle the error:

```rust
// Propagate the error
event.emit()?;

// Or handle it explicitly
if let Err(e) = event.emit() {
    // log or handle the failure
}
```

## See Also

- [#[neo_contract]](/sdk/macros/neo-contract/) -- the contract macro that provides the runtime context
- [Manifest Overlays](/concepts/manifest-overlays/) -- how event metadata merges into the manifest
- [NEP-17 Fungible Token](/standards/nep17/) -- standard that requires the `Transfer` event

import { Aside } from '@astrojs/starlight/components';

`#[neo_safe]` marks a standalone exported function as safe (read-only) in the generated manifest. It is the free-function counterpart to `#[neo_method(safe)]`, which works inside `#[neo_contract] impl` blocks.

## Basic Usage

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;

#[neo_safe]
#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn get_name() -> i64 {
    // return name string pointer
    0
}
```

The macro wraps the function and emits a Wasm custom section containing:

```json
{
  "abi": {
    "methods": [
      { "name": "get_name", "safe": true }
    ]
  }
}
```

The translator reads this metadata and sets `"safe": true` on the matching method in the manifest.

## When to Use

Use `#[neo_safe]` when you have standalone `extern "C"` functions that are not part of a `#[neo_contract] impl` block. This is common in two scenarios:

### 1. Contracts Without the Struct Pattern

Some contracts are written as flat modules with free functions instead of using the struct + impl pattern:

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;

#[neo_safe]
#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn total_supply() -> i64 {
    1_000_000
}

#[neo_safe]
#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn symbol() -> i64 {
    // return string pointer
    0
}

#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn transfer(from: i64, to: i64, amount: i64) -> i64 {
    // state-mutating -- no #[neo_safe]
    if from > 0 && to > 0 && amount > 0 { 1 } else { 0 }
}
```

### 2. Utility Exports Alongside a Contract Struct

Sometimes a contract needs additional exports that do not belong to the main impl block:

```rust
#[neo_contract]
pub struct MyToken;

#[neo_contract]
impl MyToken {
    #[neo_method(safe)]
    pub fn balance_of(account: i64) -> i64 { 0 }

    #[neo_method]
    pub fn transfer(from: i64, to: i64, amount: i64) -> bool { true }
}

// Additional utility export outside the impl block
#[neo_safe]
#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn contract_version() -> i64 {
    1
}
```

## Comparison with `#[neo_method(safe)]`

| Feature | `#[neo_method(safe)]` | `#[neo_safe]` |
|---|---|---|
| Placement | Inside `#[neo_contract] impl` | Any `fn` item |
| Export shim generation | Automatic (from `#[neo_contract]`) | Manual (`#[no_mangle] pub extern "C"`) |
| Parameter marshalling | Automatic | Manual |
| Manifest safe flag | Yes | Yes |
| Name conversion | Automatic `snake_case` to `camelCase` | Uses the function name as-is |

<Aside type="tip">
  Prefer `#[neo_method(safe)]` inside a `#[neo_contract] impl` block whenever possible. It handles export naming, parameter marshalling, and ABI metadata automatically. Use `#[neo_safe]` only for standalone functions that need to be exported outside the contract struct pattern.
</Aside>

## How It Works

The macro does two things:

1. Preserves the original function unchanged.
2. Emits a manifest overlay custom section that marks the function name as safe.

The function name used in the overlay is taken from the `fn` identifier. If you use `#[no_mangle]`, the Wasm export name matches the Rust function name exactly.

```rust
#[neo_safe]
#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn get_balance() -> i64 { 0 }
// Overlay: { "abi": { "methods": [{ "name": "get_balance", "safe": true }] } }
```

## Complete Example

A minimal contract using only free functions and `#[neo_safe]`:

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;

neo_manifest_overlay!(
    r#"{
    "name": "SimpleQuery",
    "supportedstandards": []
}"#
);

const OWNER: i64 = 1;
const TOTAL: i64 = 500_000;

#[neo_safe]
#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn get_owner() -> i64 {
    OWNER
}

#[neo_safe]
#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn get_total() -> i64 {
    TOTAL
}

#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn set_total(new_total: i64) -> i64 {
    // state-mutating, not marked safe
    if new_total > 0 { 1 } else { 0 }
}
```

The generated manifest will have `get_owner` and `get_total` marked as `"safe": true`, while `set_total` defaults to `"safe": false`.

## See Also

- [#[neo_method]](/sdk/macros/neo-method/) -- the preferred way to mark methods as safe inside impl blocks
- [Manifest Macros](/sdk/macros/manifest-macros/) -- `neo_safe_methods!` for batch-declaring safe methods
- [Manifest Overlays](/concepts/manifest-overlays/) -- how safe flags merge into the manifest

import { Aside } from '@astrojs/starlight/components';

`#[neo_storage]` generates storage persistence methods for a Rust struct. The macro adds `load()`, `load_result()`, and `save()` methods that serialize the struct to and from Neo contract storage using a deterministic key derived from the struct name.

## Basic Usage

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;
use neo_devpack::serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

#[derive(Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[neo_storage]
pub struct ContractState {
    balances: NeoMap<NeoByteString, NeoInteger>,
    owner: NeoByteString,
    total_supply: NeoInteger,
}
```

This generates an `impl ContractState` block with three methods:

| Method | Signature | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `load` | `fn load(context: &NeoStorageContext) -> Self` | Load from storage, return `Default` on error |
| `load_result` | `fn load_result(context: &NeoStorageContext) -> NeoResult<Self>` | Load from storage, propagate errors |
| `save` | `fn save(&self, context: &NeoStorageContext) -> NeoResult<()>` | Serialize and write to storage |

## Storage Key

The storage key is derived from the struct name using the pattern `{StructName}::storage`. For `ContractState`, the key is `ContractState::storage`.

All fields are serialized together into a single storage entry under this key. This means the entire struct is read and written as one unit.

```rust
// Key: "ContractState::storage"
let context = NeoRuntime::get_storage_context()?;
let state = ContractState::load(&context);
```

<Aside type="note">
  The single-key approach is simple and works well for small to medium state. For contracts with large or frequently-updated individual fields, consider using direct `NeoStorage` calls with per-field keys instead.
</Aside>

## Loading State

### `load` -- Infallible

Returns the deserialized struct or `Default::default()` if the key does not exist or deserialization fails:

```rust
let context = NeoRuntime::get_storage_context()?;
let state = ContractState::load(&context);
// state is either the persisted value or Default::default()
```

### `load_result` -- Fallible

Returns `NeoResult<Self>`, allowing the caller to handle errors explicitly:

```rust
let context = NeoRuntime::get_storage_context()?;
match ContractState::load_result(&context) {
    Ok(state) => {
        // use state
    }
    Err(e) => {
        // handle deserialization error
    }
}
```

If the storage key does not exist (empty bytes), `load_result` returns `Ok(Self::default())` rather than an error.

## Saving State

`save` serializes the struct and writes it to storage. It checks for read-only contexts and returns an error if the context does not allow writes:

```rust
let context = NeoRuntime::get_storage_context()?;
let mut state = ContractState::load(&context);

state.total_supply = NeoInteger::new(1_000_000);
state.owner = NeoRuntime::get_calling_script_hash()?;

state.save(&context)?;
```

<Aside type="caution">
  Calling `save` on a read-only storage context returns `Err(NeoError::InvalidOperation)`. This happens when the function is invoked via a safe (read-only) call. Only state-mutating methods should call `save`.
</Aside>

## Required Trait Bounds

The generated methods require these trait implementations on the struct:

| Method | Required traits |
|---|---|
| `load` | `Default` + `DeserializeOwned` |
| `load_result` | `Default` + `DeserializeOwned` |
| `save` | `Serialize` |

The simplest way to satisfy these is with derive macros:

```rust
#[derive(Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[neo_storage]
pub struct MyState {
    // fields...
}
```

## Practical Example

A complete contract using `#[neo_storage]` for persistent state:

```rust
use neo_devpack::prelude::*;
use neo_devpack::serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

neo_manifest_overlay!(
    r#"{
    "name": "StorageExample",
    "supportedstandards": []
}"#
);

#[derive(Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[neo_storage]
pub struct AppState {
    counters: NeoMap<NeoString, NeoInteger>,
    settings: NeoMap<NeoString, NeoValue>,
}

#[neo_contract]
pub struct StorageApp;

#[neo_contract]
impl StorageApp {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self
    }

    #[neo_method]
    pub fn increment(counter_name: i64) -> i64 {
        let context = match NeoRuntime::get_storage_context() {
            Ok(ctx) => ctx,
            Err(_) => return 0,
        };

        let mut state = AppState::load(&context);
        let key = NeoString::from_str("default");
        let current = state
            .counters
            .get(&key)
            .cloned()
            .unwrap_or(NeoInteger::zero());
        let next = current + NeoInteger::one();
        let result = next.as_i64_saturating();
        state.counters.insert(key, next);
        let _ = state.save(&context);

        result
    }

    #[neo_method(safe)]
    pub fn get_count() -> i64 {
        let context = match NeoRuntime::get_storage_context() {
            Ok(ctx) => ctx,
            Err(_) => return 0,
        };

        let state = AppState::load(&context);
        let key = NeoString::from_str("default");
        state
            .counters
            .get(&key)
            .map(|v| v.as_i64_saturating())
            .unwrap_or(0)
    }
}
```

## Multiple Storage Structs

A contract can define multiple `#[neo_storage]` structs. Each gets its own storage key:

```rust
#[derive(Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[neo_storage]
pub struct UserStore {
    users: NeoMap<NeoByteString, NeoValue>,
}
// Key: "UserStore::storage"

#[derive(Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[neo_storage]
pub struct ConfigStore {
    settings: NeoMap<NeoString, NeoValue>,
}
// Key: "ConfigStore::storage"
```

This is useful for separating concerns -- user data and configuration live in different storage entries and can be loaded independently.

## Storage Cost Considerations

Every `load` reads the entire serialized struct from storage, and every `save` writes it back. For contracts with large state:

- Minimize the number of `load`/`save` round-trips per method call.
- Load once at the start of a method, mutate in memory, and save once at the end.
- Consider splitting large state across multiple `#[neo_storage]` structs so you only load what you need.

```rust
// Good: one load, one save
#[neo_method]
pub fn batch_update(&mut self) -> NeoResult<()> {
    let context = NeoRuntime::get_storage_context()?;
    let mut state = AppState::load(&context);

    // multiple mutations in memory
    state.counters.insert(NeoString::from_str("a"), NeoInteger::one());
    state.counters.insert(NeoString::from_str("b"), NeoInteger::new(2));

    state.save(&context)?;
    Ok(())
}
```

